INSERT INTO `aove_options` (`option_id`, `attribute_id`, `perent_id`, `title`, `image_name`, `content`, `status`) VALUES
(1, 1, 3, 'Germany', 'gmcode/aove/German_Shepherd.png', '<div class="country-div-wrap">\r\n<table class="country-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <img alt="Germany" src="{{media url="wysiwyg/flags/germany.jpg"}}" />\r\n    </td>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> German </h1>\r\n      <h1 class="gray-h"> Spirit History </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e" colspan="2">\r\n      <p> Beer is a major part of German culture. For many years German beer was brewed in adherence to the Reinheitsgebot order or law which only permitted water, hops, and malt as beer ingredients. The order also required that beers not exclusively using barley-malts such as wheat beer must be top-fermented. Since 1993, the production of beer has been governed by the Provisional German Beer Law which allows a greater range of ingredients (only in top-fermenting beers) and additives, that have to be completely, or at least as much as possible, removed from the final product. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(2, 1, 1, 'Germany', 'gmcode/aove/German_Shepherd.png', '<div class="country-div-wrap">\r\n<table class="country-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <img alt="Germany" src="{{media url="wysiwyg/flags/germany.jpg"}}" />\r\n    </td>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> German </h1>\r\n      <h1 class="gray-h"> Beer History </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e" colspan="2">\r\n      <p> Beer is a major part of German culture. For many years German beer was brewed in adherence to the Reinheitsgebot order or law which only permitted water, hops, and malt as beer ingredients. The order also required that beers not exclusively using barley-malts such as wheat beer must be top-fermented. Since 1993, the production of beer has been governed by the Provisional German Beer Law which allows a greater range of ingredients (only in top-fermenting beers) and additives, that have to be completely, or at least as much as possible, removed from the final product. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(3, 1, 1, 'Australia', 'gmcode/aove/Border_Collie.png', '<div class="country-div-wrap">\r\n<table class="country-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <img alt="Australia" src="{{media url="wysiwyg/flags/aus.gif"}}" />\r\n    </td>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Australian </h1>\r\n      <h1 class="gray-h"> Beer History </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e" colspan="2">\r\n      <p> As Australia is a relatively young country their history with beer is very short and heavily influenced by both traditional English styles and new world American styles with the big brands generally focusing on the former and the craft breweries the latter. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(4, 1, 1, 'Belgium', 'gmcode/aove/st_bernard.png', '<div class="country-div-wrap">\r\n<table class="country-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <img alt="Belgium" src="{{media url="wysiwyg/flags/belgium.png"}}" />\r\n    </td>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Begian </h1>\r\n      <h1 class="gray-h"> Beer History </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e" colspan="2">\r\n      <p> Beer in Belgium dates back to the age of the first crusades in the 1100s, long before Belgium became an independent country. Under Catholic Church permission, local French and Flemish abbeys brewed and distributed beer as a fund raising method. The relatively low-alcohol beer of that time was preferred as a sanitary option to available drinking water. What are now traditional, artisanal brewing methods evolved, under abbey supervision, during the next seven centuries. The Trappist monasteries that now brew beer in Belgium were occupied in the late 18th century primarily by monks fleeing the French Revolution. However, the first Trappist brewery in Belgium (Westmalle) did not start operation until 10 December 1836, almost 50 years after the Revolution. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(5, 1, 1, 'England', 'gmcode/aove/British_Bulldog.png', '<div class="country-div-wrap">\r\n<table class="country-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <img alt="England" src="{{media url="wysiwyg/flags/england.jpg"}}" />\r\n    </td>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> English </h1>\r\n      <h1 class="gray-h"> Beer History </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e" colspan="2">\r\n      <p> Beer was one of the most common drinks during the Middle Ages. Since the purity of water could seldom be guaranteed, alcoholic drinks were a popular choice, having been boiled as part of the brewing process. As brewing became more organized and reliable many inns and taverns ceased brewing for themselves and bought beer from these early commercial breweries.\r\nThe use of hops in beer can be dated back as early as 822 by a Carolingian Abbot. Flavouring beer with hops was only gradually adopted because of difficulties in establishing the right proportions of ingredients. Before that, gruit, a mix of various herbs had been used, but did not have the same conserving properties as hops. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(6, 1, 2, 'England', 'gmcode/aove/British_Bulldog.png', '<div class="country-div-wrap">\r\n<table class="country-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <img alt="England" src="{{media url="wysiwyg/flags/england.jpg"}}" />\r\n    </td>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> English </h1>\r\n      <h1 class="gray-h"> Cider History </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e" colspan="2">\r\n      <p> Cider has been a staple of the British hearth for nearly a thousand years, if not more. In 55 BC, the Romans upon their first travels to what they called Britannia found the native population already living there making a type of cider in what is present day Kent from the apples they already had.\r\nSaxon chronicles before their conquest of British Celts mention cider-like drinks and also mention the production of a drink called æppelwīn, an ancient cognate of the Modern German ’apfelwein’’, both literally meaning a wine or alcohol made from apples. Today England is world renowned for its production of many different styles of cider, from still to sparkling and scrumpy to sweet and it is home to some of the best cideries in the world. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(7, 1, 2, 'Franc', 'gmcode/aove/Poodle.png', '<div class="country-div-wrap">\r\n<table class="country-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <img alt="Franc" src="{{media url="wysiwyg/flags/France.png"}}" />\r\n    </td>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> French </h1>\r\n      <h1 class="gray-h"> Cider History </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e" colspan="2">\r\n      <p> Cider came to France by way of Kazakhstan. As caravans travelled west from where apples originated, the travellers discarded their apple cores and seeds on the roadside. These seeds grew into fruit-bearing apple trees and, eventually, made their way to modern day Brittany and Normandy, where the cooler climate proved difficult for grape production but ideal for apple cultivation.\r\nThere are mentions of cider making in Normandy and Brittany as early as the middle ages and Charlemagne even documented the consumption of French cider in the early 10th century. But it was with the invention of the cider press in the 13th century that helped secure cider''s place at the French table and ensure it became a mainstay of the culture producing a number of dry traditional style ciders. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(8, 1, 3, 'Franc', 'gmcode/aove/Poodle.png', '<div class="country-div-wrap">\r\n<table class="country-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <img alt="Franc" src="{{media url="wysiwyg/flags/France.png"}}" />\r\n    </td>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> French </h1>\r\n      <h1 class="gray-h"> Spirit History </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e" colspan="2">\r\n      <p> Spirit History - Description </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(9, 1, 1, 'New Zealand', 'gmcode/aove/Brown_Border_Collie.png', '<div class="country-div-wrap">\r\n<table class="country-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <img alt="New Zealand" src="{{media url="wysiwyg/flags/nz.jpg"}}" />\r\n    </td>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> New Zealand </h1>\r\n      <h1 class="gray-h"> Beer History </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e" colspan="2">\r\n      <p> As New Zealand is a relatively young country their history with beer is very short and heavily influenced by both traditional English styles and new world American styles with the big brands generally focusing on the former and the craft breweries the latter. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(10, 1, 2, 'New Zealand', 'gmcode/aove/Brown_Border_Collie.png', '<div class="country-div-wrap">\r\n<table class="country-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <img alt="New Zealand" src="{{media url="wysiwyg/flags/nz.jpg"}}" />\r\n    </td>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> New Zealand </h1>\r\n      <h1 class="gray-h"> Cider History </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e" colspan="2">\r\n      <p> In New Zealand, according to the Food Standards Code, cider is a "fruit wine prepared from the juice or must of apples and no more than 25% of the juice or must of pears". So no minimum apple content is stipulated and there is nothing to distinguish between ciders made from fresh apple juice or concentrate.\r\nAs is the case with their beer history, New Zealand have a relatively short history with Cider, being influenced heavily by English cider making traditions. However New Zealand’s vast array of climates means that they can grow and produce a wide variety of apples in one orchard. This gives them the freedom to make ciders that fit into many different categories and over the last decade have become known for their range of vastly different ciders. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(11, 1, 1, 'Norway', 'gmcode/aove/Norwegian_Lapphund.png', '<div class="country-div-wrap">\r\n<table class="country-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <img alt="Norway" src="{{media url="wysiwyg/flags/norway.png"}}" />\r\n    </td>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Norwegian </h1>\r\n      <h1 class="gray-h"> Beer History </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e" colspan="2">\r\n      <p> Beer in Norway has a long history, going back at least 1000 years. Until around 200 years ago no farm was complete without a brewhouse. From the early 20th century brewing was industrialized and home brewing outlawed. Since then, significant consolidation in the brewing sector has reduced the number of major breweries to just a handful. With the exception of the malty juleøl (Christmas beer), most beer styles brewed in Norway today trace their ancestry to central Europe. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(12, 1, 3, 'Norway', 'gmcode/aove/Norwegian_Lapphund.png', '<div class="country-div-wrap">\r\n<table class="country-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <img alt="Norway" src="{{media url="wysiwyg/flags/norway.png"}}" />\r\n    </td>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Norwegian </h1>\r\n      <h1 class="gray-h"> Spirit History </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e" colspan="2">\r\n      <p> Spirit Description </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(13, 1, 3, 'Scotland', 'gmcode/aove/Scottish_Terrier.png', '<div class="country-div-wrap">\r\n<table class="country-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <img alt="Scotland" src="{{media url="wysiwyg/flags/Scotland.jpg"}}" />\r\n    </td>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Scottish </h1>\r\n      <h1 class="gray-h"> Spirit History </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e" colspan="2">\r\n      <p> Scottish Spirit History Description </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(14, 1, 1, 'Scotland', 'gmcode/aove/Scottish_Terrier.png', '<div class="country-div-wrap">\r\n<table class="country-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <img alt="Scotland" src="{{media url="wysiwyg/flags/Scotland.jpg"}}" />\r\n    </td>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Scottish </h1>\r\n      <h1 class="gray-h"> Beer History </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e" colspan="2">\r\n      <p> Brewing in Scotland goes back 5,000 years with ales that would have been Gruit styled. The use of bittering herbs such as heather, myrtle, and broom to flavour and preserve beer continued long after the rest of the UK had adopted hops in its beer. So many of Scotlands traditional brews are unhopped and focus more on the malt driven styles such as scotch ales, red ales, porters and stouts. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(15, 1, 1, 'USA', 'gmcode/aove/American_Pitbull.png', '<div class="country-div-wrap">\r\n<table class="country-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <img alt="USA" src="{{media url="wysiwyg/flags/USA.png"}}" />\r\n    </td>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> American </h1>\r\n      <h1 class="gray-h"> Beer History </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e" colspan="2">\r\n      <p> Until the middle of the 19th century, British-style ales dominated American brewing. This changed when the lager styles, brought by German immigrants, turned out to be more profitable for large-scale manufacturing and shipping. Despite only staying in business for seven years (1976-83), New Albion (America’s first Brewpub) ignited an interest in craft beer and set a precedent for a generation of craft brewers, including Ken Grossman of Sierra Nevada fame. Since then almost 3,000 Brewpubs have popped up in America with no sign of slowing down. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(16, 1, 3, 'USA', 'gmcode/aove/American_Pitbull.png', '<div class="country-div-wrap">\r\n<table class="country-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <img alt="USA" src="{{media url="wysiwyg/flags/USA.png"}}" />\r\n    </td>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> American </h1>\r\n      <h1 class="gray-h"> Spirit History </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="country-tg-031e" colspan="2">\r\n      <p> Until the middle of the 19th century, British-style ales dominated American brewing. This changed when the lager styles, brought by German immigrants, turned out to be more profitable for large-scale manufacturing and shipping. Despite only staying in business for seven years (1976-83), New Albion (America’s first Brewpub) ignited an interest in craft beer and set a precedent for a generation of craft brewers, including Ken Grossman of Sierra Nevada fame. Since then almost 3,000 Brewpubs have popped up in America with no sign of slowing down. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(17, 2, 1, 'Moon Dog', 'gmcode/aove/MoonDog Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Moon Dog </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> Moon Dog Craft Brewery was formed when two brothers and their mate decided to join forces in their passion for unique beers. As one of Melbourne’s newest microbreweries, Moon Dog have set out to create beers that combine styles and use unusual ingredients. With a constantly changing line-up and only four core beers Moon Dog manage to keep their beers fresh and exciting! </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(18, 2, 1, 'Temple', 'gmcode/aove/temple logo trans.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Temple </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> Temple Brewing first set up shop in 2006, their first brew; Temple Pale Ale was very successful but the founders were forced to brew out of other breweries using their equipment when they were not, leading to a lack of supply to meet their huge demand. In 2009 they bit the bullet and went all in purchasing a building in Brunswick, Vic and by 2011 it was up and running and through liquidations and re-building they have managed to come out on top with no signs of letting up. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(19, 2, 1, 'Brasserie du Bocq', 'gmcode/aove/BOCQ Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Brasserie du Bocq </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> Brasserie du Bocq was set up in 1858 by Martin BELOT, a farmer in Pernode, and began when Martin started brewing beer at his farm.  The brewery produced a very wide range of products, from table beers to strong beers, passing through a large mix of densities, colours, bitterness units and tastes. Still 100% family owned, Brasserie du Bocq remains one of the last traditional Belgian breweries.  </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(20, 2, 1, 'Brasserie Dupont', 'gmcode/aove/Dupont Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Brasserie Dupont </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> Brasserie Dupont is a co-writer of Belgian beer history. Situated in Tourpes, in the centre of West-Hainaut, and incorporating an old farm, the brewery has been producing wonderful, unique beers since 1844. Their specialty, is in producing saisons – which are traditionally light and spicy beers brewed for the summer and hotter months with a low terminal gravity making them remarkably dry and refreshing.  </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(21, 2, 1, 'Cantillon', 'gmcode/aove/Cantillon Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Cantillon </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> Steeped in history and tradition, Cantillon is held in the highest regard amongst beer connoisseurs worldwide. Cantillon beers are sour, funky and unique - they are the traditional style sour beers brewed as they were when the brewery first opened over 100 years ago. Cantillon beers are some of the most sour beers in the world. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(22, 2, 1, 'Lindemans', 'gmcode/aove/Lindemans Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Lindemans </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> Eight generations ago, in 1809, the Lindemans family owned a farm in Vlezenbeek near Brussels. They decided to intensify Lambic brewing activities during winter, when less farm work had to be done. This style can only truly be produced in a specific region of Belgium from local barley, unmalted wheat, and aged or "debittered" hops, and matured in oak casks housing wild bacteria in the breweries cellars. The result is a light bodied but intensely sour and complex beer. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(23, 2, 1, 'St Bernardus', 'gmcode/aove/St Bernardus Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> St Bernardus </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> Shortly after the Second World War, the Trappist Monastery St.Sixtus in Westvleteren was looking for somebody to commercialise their beer because they did not want to do that themselves anymore. They gave a license to a cheese factory, and Brewery St.Bernard was founded. The brew master from Westvleteren, Mathieu Szafranski (from Polish origin) became a partner in the brewery and brought along the recipes, the know-how and the St.Sixtus yeast strain. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(24, 2, 1, 'Tilquin', 'gmcode/aove/Tilquin Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Tilquin </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> The Gueuzerie Tilquin began operations in February 2009. It was 12 years since a new gueuze-producer had emerged in Brabant. Installed in Bierghes in the Senne valley, the Gueuzerie Tilquin is the only gueuze blendery in Wallonia and is run by Pierre Tilquin who has worked at 3 Fonteinen and Cantillon. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(25, 2, 1, 'Charles Wells', 'gmcode/aove/Charles Wells Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Charles Wells </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> In 2006 the amalgamation of two of Britain’s most respected breweries created Wells and Young’s. Wells & Young’s Brewing Company Ltd is now a leading supplier of specialty beers in Britain and one of the top three brewers of cask beer in the country, with two of the fastest growing national brands, Young’s Bitter and Wells Bombardier. They also produce the ‘World famous’ Double Chocolate Stout and a range of fine English ales under both the Wells and Young’s brands. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(26, 2, 1, 'St Peters', 'gmcode/aove/St Peters Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> St Peters </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> The St. Peter’s Brewing Company is based at St. Peter, South Elmham, near Bungay in Suffolk. Locally malted barley is used, together with Kentish hops to produce a range of classical English cask-conditioned ales. In addition the company produces a range of superb bottled beers. St. Peter’s aim is to carry on traditional brewing practices but hope always to have something new and exciting for you to try. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(27, 2, 1, 'Theakston', 'gmcode/aove/Theakston Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Theakston </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> Since Robert Theakston first took a lease on The Black Bull Inn and Brewhouse in 1827, Theakstons is a brewer that has become synonymous with award winning creamy ales and in particular – the legendary Old Peculier. It''s taken around 180 years for Theakstons'' range of classic and seasonal ales to develop into the legend that they are today. The brewery has seen numerous changes during that time including ownership battles and development of many of the traditions still in existence today. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(28, 2, 1, 'Timothy Taylor', 'gmcode/aove/Timothy Taylor Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Timothy Taylor </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> The brewery remains in the Taylor family and is now the last independent brewery of its type left in West Yorkshire. This independence enables Taylors to survive as one of the few brewers still brewing true cask ales in the same way it has always done. To Timothy Taylor, flavour is all important. By brewing with the best Malt and Hops, outstanding beers are produced naturally with better keeping qualities, a wonderful head and superior flavour. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(29, 2, 2, 'Henneys', 'gmcode/aove/HENNEYS LOGO.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Henneys </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> England Cider </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(30, 2, 2, 'Domaine Dupont', 'gmcode/aove/Domaine Dupont Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Domaine Dupont </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> The Dupont Family has run 30 hectares of apple cider orchards for over 4 generations. The soils of the Domain, produce fruits with low yields that are rich and complex which allows them to produce a large range of traditional and innovative products. Today, there are 27 hectares of typical varieties, 6000 apple trees, for the production of Cider, Pommeau and Calvados. Domain Dupont is fully committed to producing the best quality.  Quality always comes first, often at the expense of the yield. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(31, 2, 3, 'Domaine Dupont', 'gmcode/aove/Domaine Dupont Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Domaine Dupont </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> The Dupont Family has run 30 hectares of apple cider orchards for over 4 generations. The soils of the Domain, produce fruits with low yields that are rich and complex which allows them to produce a large range of traditional and innovative products. Today, there are 27 hectares of typical varieties, 6000 apple trees, for the production of Cider, Pommeau and Calvados. Domain Dupont is fully committed to producing the best quality.  Quality always comes first, often at the expense of the yield. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(32, 2, 1, 'Schlenkerla', 'gmcode/aove/Schlenkerla Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Schlenkerla </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> Bamberg and Smokebeer ("Rauchbier") belong together. In Bamberg the greatest of these breweries is Schlenkerla: the most productive, most visited and most traditional Smokebeer source in Bamberg. Anyone who did not come here and try the strong, unmistakable taste of Original Aecht Schlenkerla Rauchbier cannot claim to have been to Bamberg. After mixing it with premium-class hops in the brew, it matures in 700 year old cellars, deep down in the hills of Bamberg, into a mellow, magnificent-tasting beer. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(33, 2, 1, 'Sunner', 'gmcode/aove/Sunner Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Sunner </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> The Sünner brewery and distillery was founded in 1830 by Christian Sünner in Köln (Cologne) and is the oldest existing brewery in the city. Kölsch- is a beer brewed exclusively by the breweries in Köln. The beer style has been around for several centuries, but was never called Kölsch until the Sünner brewery labeled it as such in 1906, and hence, claim invention of the style. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(34, 2, 1, 'Weihenstephan', 'gmcode/aove/Weihenstephan Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Weihenstephan </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> ‘World’s Oldest Brewery’, The ‘Sacred Stephen’ or Weihenstephan brewery overlooks the town of Freising in Germany. In 1040AD, the city granted Abbot Arnold the right to brew and sell beer- making them the World’s first licensed brewery.\r\nToday’s modern commercial brewery and the world’s best known ‘University of Brewing’ occupy the former monastery buildings. Weihenstephan combines hundreds of years of brewing experience with the most up-to-date brewing technology and innovation. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(35, 2, 1, 'Weltenburger', 'gmcode/aove/Weltenburger Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Weltenburger </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> The first references to a brewery in the Weltenburg monastery are to be found in the Weltenburg Nekrologium, in which it cites the death of a brewer hundreds of years ago. Another scientifically recognized source is a recorded entry in the “Libellus Traditionum” which is over 900 years old and claims the monastery as a brewery, thus Weltenburg Brewery can justifiably claim to be the oldest monastic brewery in the world. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(36, 2, 1, 'Nogne O', 'gmcode/aove/Nogne O Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Nogne O </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> Nøgne Ø''s subtitle - "The Uncompromising Brewery" is a statement of their mission to craft ales of the highest quality. Nøgne Ø has grown from a 300 hl production in 2003 to an estimated 3500 hl production in 2010. They make more than 20 different styles of ales, and export more than 70% of their total production. They do not aim to become much bigger, but will always focus on being better! </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(37, 2, 3, 'Nogne O', 'gmcode/aove/Nogne O Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Nogne O </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> Nøgne Ø''s subtitle - "The Uncompromising Brewery" is a statement of their mission to craft ales of the highest quality. Nøgne Ø has grown from a 300 hl production in 2003 to an estimated 3500 hl production in 2010. They make more than 20 different styles of ales, and export more than 70% of their total production. They do not aim to become much bigger, but will always focus on being better! </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(38, 2, 1, 'BrewDog', 'gmcode/aove/BREWDOG LOGO.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> BrewDog </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> Founded by two friends in 2007 BrewDog has developed into one of the biggest Craft breweries in the world, becoming synonymous with some of the weirdest and most creative brews on the market; including one served out of a taxidermied deer head. They are also known for their fan service, often changing recipes or creating new beers based on customer feedback. With 13 Bars, 224 employees and 14000 shareholders they show no signs of slowing down! </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(39, 2, 1, 'Darach Mor', 'gmcode/aove/Darach Mor Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Darach Mor </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> Darach Mòr is Sweden’s first whiskey cask aged brown ale. By brewing one base brown ale that is then aged in different whiskey casks they create a perfect base for the flavour that is imparted by a cask. Each brew is restricted from 550 to 800 bottles and each cask used only once so that no bottle has a lesser impact than any other. Each bottle is akin to a rare whiskey as it will never be reproduced in the same way! </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(40, 2, 1, 'Founders', 'gmcode/aove/Founders Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Founders </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> Mike Stephens and David Engbers started to gain fame when they moved away from making good but unremarkable beers and decided to brew the kind of beer that got them excited in brewing in the first place; complex, in your face ales with huge aromatics, bigger body and boat loads of flavour. Founders is one of the fastest-growing craft breweries in the United States, currently ranking number 3 on ratebeer.com’s top 50 breweries in the world!  </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(41, 2, 1, 'Golden Road', 'gmcode/aove/Golden Road Brewing Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Founders </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> In 2011, beer enthusiasts Meg Gill and Tony Yanow founded Golden Road Brewing to bring fresh beer to the local market in the most sustainable way possible.  Golden Road is committed to engaging and supporting the growing community of socially-minded beer enthusiasts. Along with the core beers, Golden Road brewers are constantly experimenting with the freshest ingredients through a collection of rotating, seasonal and limited-edition brews including the Custom IPA Series, a line-up of diverse, hop-forward IPAs. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(42, 2, 1, 'Heretic', 'gmcode/aove/Heretic Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Heretic </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> Heretic was started by Jamil Zainasheff, one of the most awarded home brewers in history, who literally wrote the book on brewing beers to style. When he got the chance to open his own brewery, however, he put aside the idea of brewing to classic style guidelines and Heretic is the result. Ordinary beer is boring; don’t drink it! Embrace your inner heretic and join us to push the boundaries of beer flavours. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(43, 2, 1, 'Rogue', 'gmcode/aove/Rogue Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Rogue </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> Rogue </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(44, 2, 1, 'Sierra Nevada', 'gmcode/aove/Sierra Nevada Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> Sierra Nevada </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> In 1979, Ken Grossman began building a small brewery in the town of Chico, California after years in the homebrew industry and a lifetime of interest in the craft. His goal: to brew exceptional ales and lagers. Today, the Sierra Nevada Brewing Co. is considered the premier craft brewery in the United States. With a plethora of awards for their constantly widening range and with critics proclaiming it “Among the best brewed anywhere in the world.” You can see why they call themselves ‘A true pioneer of American Craft beer’ </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1),
(45, 2, 3, 'ROGUE SPIRITS', 'gmcode/aove/Rogue Spirits Logo.png', '<div class="brewery-tg-wrap">\r\n<table class="brewery-tg">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <h1 class="red-h"> ROGUE SPIRITS </h1>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td class="brewery-tg-031e">\r\n      <p> Established in 2003, Rogue Spirits creates award winning multi-ingredient small batch spirits, artisan distilled in traditional hand-crafted copper pot stills. \r\nNo chemicals, additives or preservatives are used. </p>\r\n    </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>', 1);
